    "created_at": "2023-06-13T21:27:06Z",
    "updated_at": "2023-06-13T21:27:30Z",
    "body": "@ajeetdsouza This init problem has been a huge thorn in our side for a long time. The last time we did a major restructuring of the bash init script, I posted [a comment](https://github.com/starship/starship/pull/1185#issuecomment-641721907) which basically said that if [the current] system didn't fix it, I'm not sure anything would, aside from a dedicated preexec framework.\r\n\r\nAnyways, the way starship currently works is that if there is another `PROMPT_COMMAND` registered, it [grabs the command and stores it into another string, and installs our own `PROMPT_COMMAND`](https://github.com/starship/starship/blob/master/src/init/starship.bash#LL92C1-L99C7). Then, while running `starship_precmd()`, it will [`eval` the saved string](https://github.com/starship/starship/blob/master/src/init/starship.bash#LL52C1-L53C38).\r\n\r\nWhen starship is initialized after zoxide, starship will look for jobs, then fire the zoxide hook, meaning that zoxide jobs never show up in the background jobs count (since starship has already counted background jobs before starting zoxide).\r\n\r\nWhen zoxide is initialized after starship, bash will evaluate the zoxide hook, then move to evaluate starship_precmd. Now, in most cases, frameworks that run hooks like this will background them, but it doesn't look like zoxide does this? If it doesn't background anything in the bash script, I'm as confused as you are as to why there's a background job showing up.\r\n\r\nThis is a general problem with bash for most frameworks that need to hook `PROMPT_COMMAND`: many frameworks will background their jobs to reduce latency, but if those jobs are run before `starship_precmd`, we have no way of telling whether this is a user-started job that's running in the background between prompt draws, or a short-term job run by a framework that's likely to terminate shortly after the prompt draw finishes. I'm not even sure there's a principled way to tell, short of a framework that lets you register function invocations for `PROMPT_COMMAND` and then removes those jobs from the job listing before counting.",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "pin": null,
    "reactions": {
