    "updated_at": "2023-06-14T02:33:18Z",
    "body": "@chipbuster thank you for the detailed response. This seems to be related to the way subshells are executed in Bash:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n# prints `Done    /bin/echo`.\r\necho $(/bin/echo; jobs -l)\r\n\r\n# No output.\r\n/bin/echo; jobs -l\r\n```\r\n\r\nIs there a reason why we don't use `jobs -r` to only see currently running jobs?",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
