    "created_at": "2023-06-14T08:15:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2023-06-14T08:15:05Z",
    "body": "> The idea of the jobs indicator is to indicate whether there are jobs in the background, not necessarily what's running.\r\n\r\nFair enough, but jobs marked as `Done` would not stop the shell from exiting. Perhaps they could be filtered out?\r\n\r\n> Does this imply that PROMPT_COMMANDs are executed in a subshell?\r\n\r\nNope. `PROMPT_COMMAND` can change environment variables, current directory, etc - a privilege that subshells do not have. However, subshells do have access to parent `jobs`.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThis issue only seems to happen when launching an external process. I did find two hacks that seem to fix the problem:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n# Problematic - prints `Done    /bin/echo` at every prompt.\r\nPROMPT_COMMAND='/bin/echo; jobs -l'\r\n\r\n# No output.\r\nPROMPT_COMMAND='/bin/echo & wait $!; jobs -l'\r\n\r\n# No output.\r\nPROMPT_COMMAND='\"$(/bin/echo > /dev/null)\"; jobs -l'\r\n```",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "pin": null,
    "reactions": {
      "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/starship/starship/issues/comments/1590700391/reactions",
