    "created_at": "2023-06-14T15:16:28Z",
    "updated_at": "2023-06-14T15:16:38Z",
    "body": "Filtering on the output of jobs is an interesting idea, but I prefer solutions that involve minimal output parsing where possible.\r\n\r\nI am unable to find any sort of documentation on the output of `jobs` for bash, but the POSIX man page claims that the only valid states for jobs are running, stopped, done, and some unspecified output for a job which was terminated by a signal.\r\n\r\nSince we want to select jobs which are not terminated, I think we can just do two loops over the running and stopped jobs. So instead of this:\r\n\r\n```\r\nfor job in $(jobs -p); do [[ $job ]] && ((NUM_JOBS++)); done   # Count all jobs\r\n```\r\n\r\nwe can do this:\r\n\r\n```\r\nfor job in $(jobs -pr); do [[ $job ]] && ((NUM_JOBS++)); done  # Count running jobs\r\nfor job in $(jobs -ps); do [[ $job ]] && ((NUM_JOBS++)); done  # Count stopped jobs\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis does incur an extra subshell spawn, but it seems like it works on my system to avoid counting done/signaled jobs. (There should also be a principled way of avoiding the subshell spawns since `jobs` is a builtin, but frankly I doubt it matters all that much).\r\n\r\nI guess the question that remains is whether anyone considers done/signaled jobs to be part of their background job count.",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "pin": null,
