    "created_at": "2023-06-14T15:24:19Z",
    "updated_at": "2023-06-14T15:24:19Z",
    "body": "Actually, just running `jobs` once and discarding the output will remove the `Done` jobs. So this works just as well:\r\n\r\n```\r\njobs &> /dev/null\r\nfor job in $(jobs -p); do [[ $job ]] && ((NUM_JOBS++)); done   # Count all jobs\r\n```\r\n\r\n> I guess the question that remains is whether anyone considers done/signaled jobs to be part of their background job count.\r\n\r\nIMO, we should not count `Done` jobs:\r\n\r\n- As I showed above, running the `jobs` command once removes all `Done` jobs, so the current behavior is that the user sees the background job indicator on one prompt, and then it goes away on the next prompt - I think this is confusing / inconsistent\r\n- If the job is finished executing, it doesn't really fit the definition of a running background task. Quoting from https://starship.rs/config/#jobs (emphasis mine)\r\n  > The `jobs` module shows the current number of jobs **running**.",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "pin": null,
